# Issue Sizing Rules

Use this rule when deciding how large an issue should be.

## Core Rule

Prefer small, coherent issues over broad umbrella tasks.

## A Well-Sized Issue Should

- represent one meaningful outcome
- be understandable in one pass
- be implementable without major hidden subprojects
- be reviewable without overwhelming the reviewer
- avoid bundling unrelated changes

## Split Issues When

- multiple layers are changing for unrelated reasons (e.g. parsing + persistence + UI in one issue)
- multiple different outcomes are being pursued (e.g. “add voice and history”)
- acceptance criteria are too long or mixed
- dependencies need different sequencing (e.g. auth before session, session before sets)
- one issue would likely produce an oversized PR

## GymVoice Examples to Avoid

Avoid single issues such as:

- “Implement the entire voice logging flow”
- “Add voice pipeline and session persistence”
- “Build auth and all session screens”
- any issue that really contains several independent delivery units

Prefer: “Parse voice phrase into exercise, set, weight, reps, notes” (ParseExerciseSkill) as one issue; “Persist confirmed set to backend” as another; “Group sets into superset/triset” as another when dependencies allow.

## Final Rule

If an issue would likely produce a PR that is hard to review or hard to validate, the issue is probably too large. Split it.
